</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,728,1907]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,416,980,1006]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Revised diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male differs from that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tan &amp; Japir &amp; Chung &amp; Robillard" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Tan &amp; Wahab" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[748,963,980,1006]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[748,963,980,1006]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Monseremus bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[969,1097,981,1007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[969,1097,981,1007]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by the medial processes of the tenth abdominal tergite: the inner margins and apices clearly separated (instead of touching each other). The female differs from that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tan &amp; Japir &amp; Chung &amp; Robillard" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Tan &amp; Wahab" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[369,584,1052,1078]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[369,584,1052,1078]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Monseremus bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[590,718,1053,1079]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[590,718,1053,1079]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by the lateral projections at the anterior margin of the subgenital plate larger, more bulbous (in lateral view), and longer in length than subgenital plate. Other minor differences include the male subgenital plate more squarish, ca. 1.7 times wider than long; ovipositor&gt;17.0 mm in length, longer than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tan &amp; Japir &amp; Chung &amp; Robillard" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Tan &amp; Wahab" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[235,451,1160,1186]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[235,451,1160,1186]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Monseremus bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[458,587,1161,1187]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[458,587,1161,1187]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,728,1907]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,500,1196,1223]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Description of the males.</emphasis>
Habitus and colouration similar to female described in 
<bibRefCitation author="Ingrisch, S." box="[1139,1315,1196,1223]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" pagination="1 - 278" refId="ref3318" refString="Ingrisch, S. (2018) New taxa and records of Gryllacrididae (Orthoptera, Stenopelmatoidea) from South East Asia and New Guinea with a key to the genera. Zootaxa, 4510 (1), 1 - 278. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4510.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ingrisch (2018)</bibRefCitation>
(
<figureCitation box="[1331,1424,1196,1223]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1129,1153]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1105]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[151,1436,181,1105]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Monseremus appendiculatus male: body in lateral view (A); stridulatory files on second and third tergites (B); abdominal apex in dorsal (C) and lateral (D) views. Scale bars: 5 mm (A); 1 mm (all except A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825669" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825669/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Four stridulatory files on first and second abdominal tergites, two on each tergite (
<figureCitation box="[1094,1184,1232,1259]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1129,1153]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1105]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[151,1436,181,1105]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Monseremus appendiculatus male: body in lateral view (A); stridulatory files on second and third tergites (B); abdominal apex in dorsal (C) and lateral (D) views. Scale bars: 5 mm (A); 1 mm (all except A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825669" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825669/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
): Anterior file on first tergite short with 5 peg-like teeth (n = 
<specimenCount box="[589,627,1269,1295]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="male">2♂</specimenCount>
). Second file, also on first tergite, longer, more than twice the length of anterior file, slightly curved, with 12–13 peg-like teeth (n = 
<specimenCount box="[819,857,1305,1331]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="male">2♂</specimenCount>
). Third file on second tergite angularly curved, with 15–17 peg-like teeth (n = 
<specimenCount box="[447,485,1341,1367]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="male">2♂</specimenCount>
); teeth more densely packed than second file; posterior file on second tergite nearly straight, with 16–17 peg-like teeth (n = 
<specimenCount box="[603,641,1377,1403]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="male">2♂</specimenCount>
). Second and posterior files of subequal length. Eighth abdominal tergite enlarged, longer than other tergites (
<figureCitation box="[618,764,1412,1439]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1129,1153]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1105]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[151,1436,181,1105]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Monseremus appendiculatus male: body in lateral view (A); stridulatory files on second and third tergites (B); abdominal apex in dorsal (C) and lateral (D) views. Scale bars: 5 mm (A); 1 mm (all except A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825669" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825669/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Figs 4C, 4D</figureCitation>
). Ninth abdominal tergite forming a hood (
<figureCitation box="[1259,1352,1412,1439]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1129,1153]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1105]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[151,1436,181,1105]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Monseremus appendiculatus male: body in lateral view (A); stridulatory files on second and third tergites (B); abdominal apex in dorsal (C) and lateral (D) views. Scale bars: 5 mm (A); 1 mm (all except A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825669" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825669/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). Tenth abdominal tergite with two processes in the middle; each process broadest at the base, triangular, pointing ventrally and produce into a sclerotized and obtuse apex (
<figureCitation box="[688,777,1484,1511]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
); the process not touching each other at the apex (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1424,1484,1511]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Epiproct concealed beneath tenth abdominal tergite (
<figureCitation box="[765,858,1520,1547]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Cercus long and slender, cylindrical and setose, curved internally at the posterior end, with acute apex (
<figureCitation box="[777,867,1556,1583]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate circa 1.7 times wider than long; anterior margin broadly concave; lateral margin straight, with some setae; posterior margin slightly emarginated in the middle, laterally forming a lobe where stylus is inserted (
<figureCitation box="[847,938,1628,1655]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Stylus short and stout, setose, with obtuse apex (
<figureCitation box="[219,308,1664,1691]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,728,1907]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
Measurements (in mm, n = 
<specimenCount box="[503,541,1701,1727]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="male">2♂</specimenCount>
). BL = 18.6–21.3, HL = 2.8, PL = 5.0–5.3, PW = 5.9–6.6, HFL = 13.1–15.0, HTL = 12.5–14.1.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
